F
F(x)=\int_{-\infty}^xf(t)dm(t)
m
f
\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}f(t)dm(t)=K
K \in \mathbb{R}
lim_{x\rightarrow \infty} \int_{-\infty}^xf(t)dm(t)=K
\epsilon > 0
N
x_1,x_2 \geq N
K-\int_{-\infty}^{x_1}f(t)dm(t)<\frac{\epsilon}{2}
K-\int_{-\infty}^{x_2}f(t)dm(t)<\frac{\epsilon}{2}
|F(x_1)-F(x_2)|=|\int_{-\infty}^{x_1}f(t)dm(t)-\int_{-\infty}^{x_2}f(t)dm(t)|
\leq |K-\int_{-\infty}^{x_1}f(t)dm(t)|+
|K-\int_{-\infty}^{x_2}f(t)dm(t)|<\frac{\epsilon}{2}+\frac{\epsilon}{2}=\epsilon
x_0
 |F(x) - F(x_0)| \le \int_{x_0}^x |f(t)| \, dm(t) 
f
|f|dm
m
\varepsilon > 0
\delta > 0
 |x - x_0| < \delta \Rightarrow \int_{x_0}^x |f(t)| \, dm(t) < \varepsilon 
